However, be warned. The “clone is not the original” trope is *dangerously* overused. To avoid it, the narrative must delve deeply into the philosophical questions of identity and consciousness. Is the clone merely a collection of memories and genetic code, or is she a unique individual deserving of love and respect? {Actually, {boldly, {carefully, {distinctly, {elegantly, {formidably, {gracefully, {honestly, {intelligently, {justifiably, {keenly, {logically, {methodically, {naturally, {objectively, {precisely, {quietly, {rationally, {scientifically, {thoroughly, {unreservedly, {vividly, {wisely, {xenophobically, {youthfully, {zealously}}}}}}}}}}}}}}}}}}}}}}}}}}}}}}

Ultimately, the success of this story hinges on its emotional honesty. It’s not enough to *tell* us the protagonist is falling in love again. We must *feel* his confusion, his guilt, his hope. And, of course, the clone’s own journey of self-discovery must be equally compelling. You can't make people love you, but you can make them fear you…or, in this case, *feel* something. And feeling is everything.
